KINDER MORGAN TEJAS PIPELINE LLC
STATEMENT OF GENERAL TERMS AND STANDARD OPERATING CONDITIONS FOR INTERRUPTIBLE TRANSPORTATION SERVICE RENDERED PURSUANT TO SECTION 311 (a)(2) OF THE NATURAL GAS POLICY ACT OF 1978 AND THE RULES AND REGULATIONS ADOPTED THEREUNDER INCLUDING, BUT NOT LIMITED TO, ORDER 436 ISSUED BY THE FEDERAL ENERGY REGULATORY COMMISSION
ARTICLE I. Definitions
1.1 (a) "Gas" or "gas" shall mean natural gas produced from gas wells, vaporized natural gas liquids, gas produced in association with oil (casinghead gas) and/or the residue gas resulting from processing casinghead gas and/or gas well gas. (b) "Day" or "day" shall mean the 24-hour period beginning at 7:00 a.m., local time, on one calendar day and ending at 7:00 a.m., local time, on the following calendar day. (c) "Month" or "month" shall mean the period beginning at 7:00 a.m., local time, on the first day of a calendar month and ending at 7:00 a.m., local time, on the first day of the succeeding calendar month. (d) "Year" or "year" shall mean a period of twelve (12) consecutive months beginning at 7:00 a.m., local time, on the first day of a calendar month and ending at 7:00 a.m., local time, on the same date of each succeeding twelve (12) months during the term hereof. (e) "Contract Year" shall mean a year beginning on the first day of the month in which first deliveries occur. (f) "MCF" shall mean one thousand (1,000) cubic feet. (g) "BTU" shall mean the amount of heat required to raise the temperature of one avoirdupois pound of pure water from fifty-eight and five-tenths degrees Fahrenheit (58.5?F) to fifty-nine and five-tenths degrees Fahrenheit (59.5?F)at a constant pressure of fourteen and seventy-three hundredths (14.73) Psia. Where appropriate, BTU shall mean the plural of the aforementioned definition. The term "MMBTU" shall mean one million (1,000,000) BTU. (h) "Gross Heating Value" shall mean the number of BTU's liberated by the complete combustion at constant pressure of one (1) cubic foot of gas, at a base temperature of sixty degrees Fahrenheit (60?F) and a reference pressure base as set forth in Paragraph 7.1 of Article VII with air of the same temperature and pressure of the gas, after products of combustion are cooled to the initial temperature of the gas, and after the water of the combustion is condensed to the liquid state. The Gross Heating Value of the gas shall be corrected for the water vapor content of the gas being delivered; provided, however, that if the water vapor content of the gas is seven (7) pounds or less per one million (1,000,000) cubic feet, the gas shall be assumed to be dry and no correction shall be made.
(i) "Psi" shall mean pressure, measured in units of avoirdupois pounds per square inch. "Psia" or "psia" shall mean absolute pressure (absolute vacuum used as the "zero" base of measurement) and "Psig" or "psig" shall mean gauge pressure (actual, average, or a defined atmospheric pressure used as the "zero" base of measurement). (j) "MAOP" shall mean the maximum allowable operating pressure (in psig) allowed by regulation. MAOP shall be dependent upon location and shall be subject to change from time to time. (k) "Point of Receipt" or "Receipt Point" shall mean the point or points at which Transporter shall receive gas delivered to it by Shipper, or by others for Shipper's account. (l) "Point of Delivery" or "Delivery Point" shall mean the point or points at which Transporter shall redeliver gas to Shipper, or to others for Shipper's account. (m) "Operator" shall mean the Party responsible for controlling and measuring the flow of gas at the Receipt Point or Delivery Point and maintaining, at its own expense, the measuring station serving such point. (n) "Transporter" shall mean Kinder Morgan Tejas Pipeline LLC. (o) "Shipper" shall mean the party for which Transporter transports gas. (p) "Party" shall mean either Transporter or Shipper, and the term "Parties" shall mean both Transporter and Shipper. (q) "FERC" or "Commission" shall mean the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission or any successor regulatory authority having or asserting jurisdiction to regulate matters that are the subject of this Agreement. (r) "NGPA" shall mean the Natural Gas Policy Act of 1978. (s) "Taxes" shall mean all taxes (other than ad valorem, capital stock, income or excess profit taxes, general franchise taxes imposed on corporations on account of their corporate existence or on their right to do business within the state as a foreign corporation and similar taxes), including, but not limited to, gross receipts tax, licenses, fees, municipal franchise taxes and other charges levied, assessed or made by any governmental authority on the act, right or privilege of transporting, handling or delivering gas which is measured by the volume, heat content, value or sales price or transportation fee for the gas or the gross receipts from providing transportation services. (t) "AGA" shall mean the American Gas Association. "AGA Standards" shall mean any current manual, pamphlet or recommended practice published by or under the auspices of the American Gas Association, applicable to the type of measurement equipment used hereunder, whether or not such has been accepted as an American National Standard. (u) "ANSI" shall mean the American National Standard Institute; ANSI-numbered publications have been established as "American National Standards," which implies a consensus of those substantially concerned with the scope and provisions of its contents.
ARTICLE II. Quantities and Service Provided
2.1 Subject to all of the terms and provisions hereof, Transporter shall accept at each Receipt Point a daily quantity of natural gas up to the quantity set forth in Exhibit "A" for such Receipt Point, which quantity shall hereinafter be referred to as the "Maximum Daily Quantity." Transporter shall not be obligated to accept more than one-twentieth (1/20) of the Maximum Daily Quantity during any one hour period. Transporter shall have the right to refuse to provide service or to suspend service at any Receipt Point or Delivery Point, if, in Transporter's sole opinion, deliveries of gas at any such Receipt Point or Delivery Point during any month are expected to average less than one thousand (1,000) MCF per day during such month. Transporter shall have the right to terminate this Agreement as to service at any Receipt Point or Delivery Point, if deliveries of gas at any such Receipt Point or Delivery Point during any month average less than one thousand (1,000) MCF per day during such month; provided, however, that Transporter's right to terminate shall not apply if (i) Shipper notifies Transporter in advance that Shipper does not wish to obtain service during the month of deficient deliveries or (ii) the deficiency is due to an interruption of service by Transporter.
2.2 In the event Shipper has quantities of gas available from time to time for delivery to Transporter which are in excess of the Maximum Daily Quantity, Shipper may so notify Transporter and Transporter may, at its sole discretion, accept or refuse all or any part of such excess gas. Any excess gas accepted by Transporter shall be subject to all of the terms and provisions hereof.
2.3 Transporter shall redeliver to Shipper, or for Shipper's account, at the Delivery Point a daily quantity of gas thermally equivalent to the quantity of gas received by Transporter, less fuel, if applicable. Transporter shall not be obligated to redeliver quantities of gas in excess of those designated for each Delivery Point set forth in Exhibit "B" to this Agreement.
2.4 The intent of the Parties to this Agreement is that gas be received and delivered hereunder at the same rate, and Shipper shall not, in any manner, utilize Transporter's pipeline system for storage or peaking purposes. If on any day(s) Shipper delivers a quantity of gas in excess of the quantity of gas being concurrently delivered by Transporter, Transporter shall have the right to discontinue its receipts of gas from Shipper until such time as arrangements have been made by Shipper to balance such excess. If on any day(s) Shipper receives a quantity of gas in excess of the quantity of gas being concurrently delivered to Transporter, Transporter shall have the right to discontinue its deliveries of gas to Shipper until arrangements have been made by Shipper to balance such excess. It is recognized that an exact daily balancing of receipts and deliveries may not be possible due to the inability of the Parties to control precisely such receipts and deliveries. However, Transporter, to the extent practicable, will deliver each day a quantity of gas thermally equivalent to the quantity received by Transporter that day, less fuel, if applicable.
2.5 Transporter shall provide a cumulative imbalance statement to Shipper following the end of each month. Imbalances shall be corrected insofar as practicable during the month following the month in which they occur. If, upon any cancellation or termination of this Agreement, an imbalance exists, the term hereof shall be extended for a period not to exceed an additional sixty (60) days, during which time the Party whose deliveries or redeliveries are in arrears shall eliminate its deficit and thereby achieve zero balance, unless the Parties mutually agree upon an appropriate alternative method of balancing.
2.6 The services hereunder are to be performed by Transporter on an interruptible basis, and subject to the provisions of Article IV. hereof, may be interrupted without notice, in whole or in part, from time to time in Transporter's sole discretion; provided, however, that Transporter's dispatcher will endeavor to advise (by telephone) Shipper's dispatcher of an interruption as soon as practicable either before or after such interruption. In no event shall an interruption of service constitute a breach of this Agreement, and Transporter shall not be liable to Shipper or third parties in damages or otherwise because of any interruption of service. Transporter agrees to receive and deliver quantities of gas up to Shipper's Maximum Daily Quantity only when, in Transporter's sole opinion, such receipt and delivery will not be detrimental to Transporter and will not unduly impair Transporter's operations. Shipper agrees to indemnify and hold harmless Transporter for any damages, causes of actions or claims asserted by any third parties as a result of any termination, suspension, or interruption of services hereunder by Transporter.
2.7 Gas delivered to Transporter hereunder during any day shall be delivered at as nearly a constant rate as operating conditions will permit, and Shipper shall give Transporter as much advance notice as is practicable, if Shipper desires to increase or decrease the quantity of gas being delivered at a Receipt Point at any time; provided, however, that Shipper shall give Transporter prior notice of not less than twenty-four (24) hours if Shipper desires to increase or decrease such quantities by an amount exceeding twenty-five percent (25%) in volume. Such notice(s) may be made orally or in writing; provided, however, that any oral notice shall be immediately confirmed in writing. Any notice to increase the quantity of gas Shipper is delivering hereunder at any time shall not obligate Transporter to receive from Shipper or to redeliver to Shipper quantities of gas in excess of Shipper's Maximum Daily Quantity then in effect for such point(s).
2.8 If, during any three-month period, the daily average of Shipper's deliveries of gas at any Delivery Point is less than seventy-five percent (75%) of the Maximum Daily Quantity for such point, Transporter shall have the right to adjust the Maximum Daily Quantity for such point to one hundred thirty-three percent (133%) of the actual average quantity delivered at such point during such three-month period; provided, however, that if service was interrupted by Transporter, such adjustment shall be based only upon the days in which there was no such interruption, and provided further, that if service was interrupted by Transporter for at least seventy-five percent (75%) of the three-month period, an adjustment shall not be made.
2.9 Although Shipper shall retain title to gas delivered to Transporter at the Point of Receipt hereunder it is understood and agreed that such gas received by Transporter shall constitute part of Transporter's system supply, and as such Transporter shall, subject to its obligation to deliver an equivalent quantity as provided in Paragraph 2.3 of Article II. hereof, have the absolute and unqualified right to treat such gas as its own, including, but not by way of limitation, the right to commingle such gas, to deliver molecules different from those received and to treat the molecules received in any manner, including the right to process the same, retaining in Transporter and to those claiming under Transporter other than through this Agreement, all right, title and interest to any components obtained by virtue of such processing or by virtue of liquids accumulating under natural conditions in Transporter's pipeline.
ARTICLE III. Requests for Transportation
3.1 Service by Transporter shall be made available to Shippers as soon as practicable upon receipt of bona fide requests. Transporter will accept as a bona fide request only those written requests containing all of the following information:
a) Identity of Shipper - exact legal name; type of entity; state of incorporation or state of qualification to do business; mailing and street address; name, address and phone number of primary contact for Shipper regarding the transportation arrangement.
b) Gas Quantities - Maximum quantity to be transported, stated individually in MCF's for each Point of Receipt and each Point of Delivery.
c) Gas Quality - Statement regarding quality specifications, including BTU content, for the gas to be delivered at each Point of Receipt.
d) Receipt Point- i) The point(s) of entry into Transporter's system ii) The name of all parties directly delivering gas to Transporter at such point(s).
e) Delivery Point- i) The point(s) of delivery by Transporter ii) The names of all parties directly receiving gas from Transporter at such point(s).
f) Term of Service- i) Date service is requested to commence; and ii) Date service is requested to terminate.
g) Affidavit supporting request for Section 311 transaction in sufficient detail that Transporter shall be satisfied, in its sole opinion, that the service will be on behalf of an interstate pipeline or a local distribution company served by any interstate pipeline.
h) Statement that Shipper has arranged for the delivery and receipt by any necessary third-party transporter.
i) Dispatching contact and phone number.
3.2 Requests for transportation shall be submitted not less than thirty (30) days prior to the date such transportation is requested to commence. Applications received more than ninety (90) days prior to the requested commencement of service will be returned as invalid. Transporter reserves the right to waive such requirements whenever, in Transporter's sole opinion, there is excess capacity available.
3.3 Requests will be accepted in the order in which they are received by Transporter. Requests shall be mailed to:
Kinder Morgan Tejas Pipeline LLC 500 Dallas, Suite 1000 Houston, Texas 77002 Attn: Vice President, Marketing & Transportation
3.4 Gas shall not be transported prior to a written transportation agreement being properly executed by both Parties.
ARTICLE IV. Allocation of Capacity 4.1 Capacity available for Section 311 transportation shall be subject to Transporter's own operating requirements, the availability of excess capacity in its existing facilities not required for its own use from time to time or for firm transportation arrangements, and the availability of capacity sufficient to provide the service without detriment or disadvantage to all of its intrastate customers.
4.2 If, at any time during the term of this Agreement, operating conditions on all or any portion of Transporter's system constrain Transporter's ability to transport volumes through its system, then Transporter may interrupt the service so provided thereunder in whole or in part on all or such portions of Transporter's system as may be necessary in Transporter's sole discretion in accordance with the following schedule of priorities, beginning with the first service to be interrupted and continuing in order as necessary to the last service to be interrupted.
a) Interruptible Section 311 Transportation Service rendered pursuant to Section 311(a)(2) of the NGPA and provided under the terms of agreements under which gas transportation service was requested of Transporter on or after November 1, 1985.
b) Interruptible Section 311 Transportation Service rendered pursuant to Section 311(a)(2) of the NGPA and provided under the terms of agreements under which gas was tendered for transportation by Transporter prior to November 1, 1985.
c) Intrastate Sales and Transportation Service.
Within groups a and b above, Transporter reserves the right to allocate transportation capacity to those customers paying or agreeing to pay the highest fee the FERC or any other governmental agency having jurisdiction permits Transporter to collect for the service provided.
4.3 In the event Transporter interrupts service pursuant to this Article IV. for a period continuing ten (10) days or longer, Shipper shall have the right, upon prior written notice to Transporter of not less than (10) days, to terminate this Agreement. Such right to terminate shall be Shipper's sole and exclusive remedy for any interruption of service hereunder.
4.4 Transporter shall not be obligated to modify existing facilities or to install new facilities in order to either receive gas or increase its capacity for service hereunder.
ARTICLE V. Equipment Installation
5.1 If there are existing measurement and appurtenant facilities at the Receipt Point and Delivery Point hereunder that are deemed to be adequate and operable in Transporter's sole judgement, such facilities shall be utilized. However, if Transporter, in its sole judgement, deems it necessary to install new facilities or to modify, expand or replace an existing facility in order for it to receive or deliver gas hereunder at any agreed Receipt Point and/or Delivery Point, then the construction and installation of any new facilities and the modification, expansion or replacement of any existing facilities shall be performed by Transporter at Shipper's sole cost and expense, and such facilities shall be owned by Transporter.
5.2 Notwithstanding the provisions of Paragraph 5.1 above, the Parties may mutually agree to alternative arrangements for the construction, installation and ownership of any new measurement and appurtenant facilities deemed necessary by Transporter, which alternative arrangements shall be set forth in Exhibit "C" or otherwise provided in this Agreement. Any and all facilities installed by Shipper shall be designed, constructed and installed in accordance with specifications approved by Transporter. Additionally, during the period of construction and installation of such facilities Transporter shall have the right to have its representatives present for the purpose of witnessing the work and verifying that such facilities are installed in accordance with the approved specifications.
5.3 In the event Transporter, in its sole judgement, deems it necessary to modify, replace or make major repairs to any existing measurement and/or appurtenant facility owned by Transporter through which gas is being received or delivered hereunder, Transporter shall notify Shipper of the same and shall perform such modifications, replacements or major repairs at Shipper's sole cost and expense on the same basis as is set forth in Paragraph 5.1 above, subject to Shipper's agreement to pay Transporter for the total cost of such work in accordance with the provisions of Paragraph 5.8 hereof. In the event Shipper does not so agree to pay Transporter for the total cost of the modifications, replacements or major repairs deemed necessary by Transporter, Transporter shall have the right to discontinue its receipts or deliveries of gas at the applicable location(s).
5.4 Shipper shall give Transporter written notice prior to installing any facilities within two hundred feet (200') of any facilities of Transporter.
5.5 The Parties understand that Transporter may install telemetering facilities at the Receipt and Delivery Points, which installation shall be at Shipper's sole cost and expense. Transporter, in its sole discretion, will determine when such telemetering facilities will be installed. Shipper understands that a part of the telemetering may be a remotely actuated block valve that may be closed, if necessary, by Transporter without notice to Shipper, if flowing gas is detected to be in violation of the quality specifications set forth in Article VIII.
5.6 Shipper shall, insofar as it is able, grant Transporter the right of ingress and egress and all necessary easements and rights-of-way to any fee property or leaseholds of Shipper for the purpose of constructing pipelines and other facilities (including telemetering facilities) deemed necessary by Transporter for the transportation and delivery of gas hereunder.
5.7 Shipper shall remove any facilities owned by Shipper and located on Transporter's property within sixty (60) days after termination of this Agreement; provided, however, that Transporter shall have the option to purchase said facilities at a price to be mutually agreed upon by Transporter and Shipper.
5.8 Unless otherwise agreed to in writing by the Parties, Shipper shall, in advance of Transporter's performing any construction, installation, expansion, modification, replacement or major repair pursuant to Paragraphs 5.1, 5.3, or 5.5 of this Article V, pay to Transporter, by check or bank draft of Shipper, Transporter's estimated total cost for such work. For purposes of this Agreement, total cost shall include, without limitation, labor, materials, gas lost, and overhead charges. Gas lost shall, at Transporter's option, be paid for by Shipper either in-kind or in dollars at Transporter's weighted average cost of gas during the applicable period. The receipt by Transporter of such advance payment shall be a condition precedent to Transporter's performing such work.
As soon as practicable following completion of the work by Transporter, Transporter shall render a statement, which statement shall include supporting documentation, to Shipper setting forth the total cost of the work performed. In the event the total cost of the work performed exceeds the amount advanced by Shipper for such work, Shipper shall pay Transporter the amount by which such total cost exceeds Shipper's advancement within fifteen (15) days after receipt of the aforementioned statement. In the event the total cost of the work performed is less than the amount advanced by Shipper for such work, Transporter shall refund to Shipper, without interest, the amount by which Shipper's advancement exceeds such total cost, which refund shall be made by Transporter within fifteen (15) days from the date of the aforementioned statement.
ARTICLE VI. Measuring Equipment and Testing
6.1 Transporter shall be the Operator at the Receipt Point and Delivery Point unless otherwise specified in Exhibit "C". Transporter shall designate the type of measuring equipment that shall initially be utilized; provided, however, if Transporter, after the installation of measuring equipment pursuant to Transporter's initial designation for any point hereunder, designates a different type of measuring equipment, the cost of such different measuring equipment shall be borne by Transporter. Either Party may install, maintain and operate, at its sole cost and expense, check measuring equipment; provided, however, that such equipment shall be installed in a manner that will not interfere with the operation of the other Party's measuring equipment.
6.2 Orifice meters installed in such measuring stations shall be constructed and operated in accordance with ANSI/API 2530 (AGA Report No. 3), Orifice Metering of Natural Gas and Other Related Hydrocarbon Fluids, Second Edition, dated September 1985, and any subsequent modification and amendment thereof, and shall include the use of flange connections and, where necessary, straightening vanes and pulsation dampening equipment.
6.3 Positive or turbine meters installed in such measuring stations shall be constructed and operated in accordance with the provisions of AGA Measurement Committee Report No. 6 (AGA Report No. 6) dated January 1971, when positive meters are employed, and AGA Measurement Committee Report No. 7 (AGA Report No. 7), First Revision, dated November 1984, when turbine meters are used, with any subsequent amendments or revisions of either report.
6.4 When electronic transducers and flow computers, solar and otherwise, are used, the gas shall have its volume, mass and/or energy content computed in accordance with the applicable AGA standards including, but not limited to, AGA Report Nos. 3, 5, 6 and 7 and any subsequent modification and amendments thereof. The Parties specifically agree to accept the use of these electronic devices in lieu of mechanical devices with charts.
6.5 Operator shall give reasonable notice to non-operator in order that non-operator may have representatives present to observe any installing, reading, cleaning, changing, repairing, inspecting, testing, calibrating, or adjusting of Operator's measuring equipment used in measuring or checking the measurement of receipts or deliveries of gas under this Agreement. The official charts (recordings) from such measuring equipment shall remain the property of Operator, but upon request Operator will submit its records and charts, together with calculating therefrom, to non-operator for inspection and verification, subject to return to Operator within ten (10) days after receipt thereof.
6.6 Operator shall, in the presence of non-operator's representative, if requested, verify the accuracy and, at approximately monthly intervals, adjust or calibrate all transmitting or recording devices used in the measurement of the receipt or delivery of gas hereunder. Operator shall not be required to adjust or calibrate such equipment more frequently than once in any thirty (30) day period, unless non-operator desires a special test be performed as described in Paragraph 6.7 below.
(a) If, during any test of the measuring equipment, an adjustment or calibration error is found which results in an incremental adjustment to the calculated hourly flow rate through each meter run in excess of two percent (2%) of the adjusted flow rate (whether positive or negative and using the adjusted flow rate as the percent error equation denominator), then any previous recordings of such equipment shall be corrected to zero (0) error for any period which the error existed (and which is either known definitely or agreed to by both Parties) and the total flow for the period redetermined in accordance with the provisions of Paragraph 6.8 below. If the period of error condition cannot be determined or agreed upon between the Parties, such correction shall be made over a period extending over the last one-half (½) of the time lapsed since the date of the latest test, such correction period not to exceed sixteen (16) days.
(b) If, during any test of the measuring equipment, an adjustment or calibration error is found which results in an incremental adjustment to the calculated hourly flow rate which does not exceed two percent (2%) of the adjusted flow rate (as described in part (a) of this paragraph), all prior recordings shall be considered to be accurate for quantity determination purposes.
6.7 In the event non-operator desires a special test (a test not scheduled by Operator under the provisions of Paragraph 6.6 above) of any measuring equipment, seventy-two (72) hours advance notice shall be given to Operator and both Parties shall cooperate to secure a prompt test of the accuracy of such equipment. If the measuring equipment tested is found to fall under the provisions of Paragraph 6.6(b) above or if an inspection of the primary measurement equipment indicates no problems, Operator shall have the right to bill non-operator for the cost of such special test including any labor and transportation costs pertaining to such special test and non-operator shall pay such costs.
6.8 If, for any reason, any measurement equipment is (i) out of adjustment, (ii) out of service, or (iii) out of repair and the total calculated hourly flow rate through each meter run is found to be in error by an amount of the magnitude described in Paragraph 6.6(a) above, the total quantity of gas delivered shall be redetermined in accordance with the first of the following methods which is feasible:
(a) by using the registration of any mutually agreeable metering facility, if installed and accurately registering (subject to testing as described in Paragraph 6.6 above);
(b) where parallel multiple meter runs exist, by calculation using the registration of such parallel meter runs; provided that they are measuring gas from upstream and downstream headers in common the faulty metering equipment not controlled by separate regulators and are accurately registering;
(c) by correcting the error by re-reading of the official charts, or by straightforward application of a correcting factor to the quantities recorded for the period (if the net percentage of error is ascertainable by calibration, tests or mathematical calculation);
(d) by estimating the quantity, based upon deliveries made during periods of similar conditions when the meter was registering accurately.
6.9 Operator shall retain and preserve for a period of at least two (2) years all test data, charts, and other similar records.
ARTICLE VII. Measurement Specifications
The measurements of the quantity and quality of all gas delivered at the Receipt Point and the Delivery Point hereunder shall be conducted in accordance with the following:
7.1 Unit of Volume: The unit of volume for measurement shall be one (1) cubic foot of gas at a temperature base of sixty degrees Fahrenheit (60?F) and at a pressure base of fourteen and sixty-five hundredths (14.65) psia. Such measured volumes, converted to MCF, shall be multiplied by their Gross Heating Value per cubic foot and divided by 1,000 to determine MMBTU's received and delivered hereunder.
7.2 Volume Computations: Computations of gas volumes from measurement data shall be made in accordance with the following depending upon the type of measurement Transporter has designated:
a) Orifice meters - ANSI/API 2530 (AGA Report No. 3), Orifice Metering of Natural Gas and Other Related Hydrocarbon Fluids, Second Edition, dated September 1985, and any subsequent amendments or revisions.
b) Positive and turbine meters - For positive meters AGA Measurement Committee Report No. 6 (AGA Report No. 6), dated January 1971, and any subsequent amendments or revisions. For turbine meters, AGA Measurement Committee Report No. 7 (AGA Report No. 7), First Revision, dated November, 1984, and any subsequent amendments or revisions.
c) Electronic transducers and flow computers - AGA Report Nos. 3, 5, 6 & 7 and any subsequent amendments or revisions.
7.3 Temperature Measurement: The temperature of the gas shall be determined by a recording thermometer so installed that it may record the temperature of the gas flowing through the meters. If the Parties do not consider the installation of such a recording thermometer to be necessary, other agreeable means of recording temperature may be used. The average temperature to the nearest one degree Fahrenheit (1?F), obtained while gas is being delivered, shall be the applicable flowing gas temperature for the period under consideration.
7.4 Specific Gravity Measurement: The specific gravity of the gas shall be determined by a recording gravitometer or a chromatographic device installed and located at a suitable point to record representative average specific gravity of the gas being metered or by other mutually agreeable methods. The gravity, to the nearest one-thousandth (0.001) obtained while gas is being delivered shall be the specific gravity of the gas used for the recording period. At Transporter's option spot samples or continuous sampling using standard type specific gravity sampling methods may be used in lieu of a recording gravitometer or chromatograph. If the spot sample or continuous sampling method is used, the specific gravity of the gas delivered hereunder shall be determined once a month from a gas analysis. The result shall be obtained to the nearest one-thousandth (0.001) and should be applied during the calendar month for the determination of gas volumes delivered.
7.5 Adjustment for Supercompressibility: Adjustments to measured gas volumes for the effects of supercompressibility shall be made in accordance with accepted AGA standards. Operator shall obtain representative carbon dioxide and nitrogen mole fraction values for the gas delivered or received as may be required to compute such adjustments in accordance with standard testing procedures. At Operator's option, equations for the calculation of supercompressibility may be taken from either the AGA Manual for the Determination of Supercompressibility Factors for Natural Gas, dated December, 1962 (also known as the "NX-19 Manual") or AGA Report No. 8, dated December, 1985, Compressibility and Supercompressibility for Natural Gas and Other Hydrocarbon Gases, latest revision.
7.6 Gross Heating Value: The Gross Heating Value of the gas delivered at the Receipt and Delivery Point hereunder shall be determined by using a Cutler-Hammer or other standard type calorimeter or by calculating the Gross Heating Value from an in-line chromatograph or a gas analysis of a spot or continuous gas sample. The spot or continuous sample shall be taken monthly and such sample shall be taken at a suitable point on the facilities to be representative of the gas being metered.
7.7 Other Tests: Other tests to determine water content, sulfur, and other impurities in the gas shall be conducted by Operator as necessary and shall be conducted in accordance with standard industry testing procedures. The Party requested to perform such test(s) shall bear the cost of test(s) only in the event the gas tested is determined not to be within the applicable specification(s). If the gas tested is determined to be within the applicable specifications, the requesting Party shall bear the cost of such test(s).
7.8 New Test Methods: If at any time during the term hereof a new method or technique is developed with respect to gas measurement or the determination of the factors used in such gas measurement, such new method or technique may be substituted for the method set forth in this Article when such methods or techniques are in accordance with the currently accepted standards of the American Gas Association.
ARTICLE VIII. Quality
All natural gas delivered at the Receipt Point and the Delivery Point hereunder shall conform to the following specifications:
8.1 Water Vapor: The gas shall in no event have a water vapor content in excess of seven (7) pounds of water vapor per million (1,000,000) cubic feet of gas measured at a pressure base of fourteen and sixty-five hundredths (14.65) psi and at a temperature base of sixty degrees Fahrenheit (60?F), as determined by a method generally acceptable for use in the gas industry.
8.2 Hydrogen Sulfide: The gas shall not contain more than one quarter (0.25) grain of hydrogen sulfide per hundred (100) cubic feet of gas at the Receipt Point and no more than one half (0.5) grain per hundred (100) cubic feet of gas at the Delivery Point as determined by quantitative tests. Determination shall be made by a method in general use in the industry, which method shall be mutually agreed to by all Parties.
8.3 Total Sulfur: The gas shall not contain more than two (2) grains of total sulfur per one hundred (100) cubic feet of gas. Determination shall be made by a method in general use in the industry, which method shall be mutually agreed to by all Parties.
8.4 Temperature: The gas shall not have a temperature of less than forty degrees Fahrenheit (40?F), nor more than one hundred twenty degrees Fahrenheit (120?F).
8.5 Carbon Dioxide: The gas shall not contain in excess of two percent (2%) by volume of carbon dioxide.
8.6 Oxygen: The gas shall not contain in excess of one percent (1%) by volume of oxygen.
8.7 Nitrogen: The gas shall not contain in excess of three percent (3%) by volume of nitrogen.
8.8 Non-hydrocarbons: The gas shall not contain more than four percent (4%) by volume of total non-hydrocarbons. Non-hydrocarbons shall include, but not be limited to, carbon dioxide, oxygen, nitrogen, sulfur, and hydrogen sulfide.
8.9 Objectionable Liquids and Solids and Dilution: The gas shall (1) be free of objectionable liquids and solids; (2) be commercially free from dust, gums, gum-forming constituents, or other liquids or solid matter which might become separated from the gas in the course of transportation through pipelines and (3) not be subjected to any treatment or process which will change the chemical composition of any of the component parts of such gas, permit or cause the admission of oxygen or which will dilute such gas or otherwise cause it to fail to meet the quality specifications, hereinabove identified.
8.10 Gross Heating Value: The gas shall have a Gross Heating Value of not less than nine hundred fifty (950) BTU per cubic foot nor more than one thousand one hundred fifty (1150) BTU per cubic foot, unless mutually agreed otherwise; provided, however, Transporter shall have the right to reduce the upper limit set forth above. Transporter reserves the right to refuse to provide service or to terminate service at any Receipt Point upstream of a gas processing plant if the BTU content of Shipper's gas is less than the average BTU content contained in all other gas in that portion of Transporter's system.
8.11 Failure to Meet Quality Specifications: In the event either Party determines that gas delivered to it fails to meet the quality specifications set forth in this Article VIII., such Party shall have the right to immediately terminate, without prior notice, the receipt of any gas failing to meet such quality specifications; provided, however, that such action shall, as soon as practicable thereafter, be followed by a written notice which shall include the basis therefor.
ARTICLE IX. Delivery Pressure and Assumed Atmospheric Pressure at Receipt Point
9.1 Shipper shall deliver gas to Transporter at the Receipt Point at a pressure(s) sufficient to enter Transporter's pipeline system at each such point, not to exceed the MAOP in Transporter's pipeline at each such point. The assumed atmospheric pressure at each Receipt Point shall be as set forth on Exhibit "A" regardless of variations in natural atmospheric pressure from time to time.
ARTICLE X. Delivery Pressure and Assumed Atmospheric Pressure at Delivery Point
10.1 Transporter shall deliver gas at the Delivery Point at the pressure(s) existing in Transporters pipeline system at each such point. The assumed atmospheric pressure at each Delivery Point shall be as set forth on Exhibit "B" regardless of variations in natural atmospheric pressure from time to time.
ARTICLE XI. Term
11.1 Service will be provided for an initial term agreed to by the Parties, and shall thereafter remain in force and effect unless and until terminated by either Party upon not less than thirty (30) days' prior written notice of such termination to the other Party. However, Transporter shall have the right, upon prior written notice to Shipper, to either immediately terminate this Agreement at any time or, from time to time, to immediately suspend service hereunder in the event (i) Transporter, on a non-discriminatory basis, concurrently terminates or suspends, as applicable, all NGPA Section 311 transportation service of the type provided for under this transportation arrangement, or (ii) deliveries of gas for transportation hereunder cease for any period of one hundred eighty (180) consecutive days or more. Shipper shall immediately notify Transporter by telegram or other mutually acceptable method of the occurrence of initial deliveries, which shall be by mutual agreement of the parties.
ARTICLE XII. Laws and Regulations
12.1 This Agreement shall be subject to all valid existing and future laws, orders, rules, regulations or proclamations of duly constituted authorities having jurisdiction or control over the Parties thereto or the subject matter thereof including, but not limited to, the provisions of Subpart C of Part 284 of the regulations of the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission that implement Section 311(a)(2) of the NGPA. If any such governmental authority shall take any action which is, with respect to or as a result of this Agreement, designed to subject or otherwise subjects either Party or any of its pipeline or related facilities to any greater or different regulation or jurisdiction than that existing on the date of this Agreement (or thereafter as such regulation or jurisdiction may have changed and been accepted by such Party), then upon written notice to the other, the Party so affected may cancel and terminate this Agreement effective one (1) day prior to the effective date of such governmental action without further obligation to the other Party except, in the case of Shipper, to make payment for services rendered and, in the case of either Transporter or Shipper, to correct any gas imbalance existing on the date of such termination.
12.2 Transporter shall file all necessary reports and/or notices required by Subpart C of Part 284 of the FERC's Regulations, and Shipper shall provide Transporter with any necessary compliance information requested by Transporter in connection with preparing such reports.
12.3 Transporter shall have the right to cancel the Agreement upon not less than ten (10) days written notice to Shipper, if at any time any governmental or regulatory authority or official having or asserting jurisdiction takes any action including, without limitation, issuance of a "policy statement," whereby the receipt, transportation and redelivery of gas as contemplated hereunder or pursuant to other agreements subject to Section 311(a)(2) of the NGPA shall be prohibited or subjected to terms, conditions, restraints or regulations, including rate or price controls, or ceilings or open access requirements which, in the judgement of Transporter, are unduly or overly burdensome; provided, however, that nothing contained herein shall preclude the Parties from renegotiating the Agreement if they so choose.
12.4 Shipper warrants that all gas delivered to Transporter for transportation hereunder shall be eligible for transportation under Section 311(a)(2) of the Natural Gas Policy Act and all applicable rules, regulations or orders of the FERC applicable thereto. Shipper indemnifies and holds harmless Transporter from any and all suits, actions, damages, costs, losses, expenses (including reasonable attorney fees) and regulatory proceedings arising out of or in connection with breach of said warranty. Shipper shall execute such other documents as may be required by Transporter to evidence the eligibility of gas transported.
ARTICLE XIII. Taxes and Fee Reimbursement
13.1 Transporter agrees to pay, or cause to be paid, all Taxes in effect on the effective date of this Agreement that are lawfully levied and imposed upon Transporter with respect to the transportation of gas hereunder and/or associated facilities related thereto. Shipper shall, however, reimburse Transporter for any additional or increased Taxes arising after the effective date of this Agreement that are lawfully levied upon and/or paid by Transporter with respect to such transportation and/or associated facilities.
13.2 Shipper shall reimburse Transporter for any and all filing fees that Transporter is required, by the FERC or any other governmental authority having or asserting jurisdiction, to pay in connection with the transportation services hereunder.
ARTICLE XIV. Billings and Payments
14.1 As soon as practicable each month, Transporter shall render to Shipper a statement setting forth the MCF and MMBTU delivered at the Receipt Point and Delivery Point during the preceding month and an invoice setting forth the amount of compensation due to Transporter hereunder. Such statement and invoice shall include information sufficient to explain and support both the aforementioned amounts and any adjustments thereto and shall be mailed or electronically transmitted on the same day as the invoice date.
14.2 Shipper shall pay Transporter for all amounts set forth in Transporter's invoice within ten (10) days from the date of such invoice. In the event any billing or statement is disputed by Shipper, Shipper shall pay the undisputed amount and shall, within (10) days from the date of Transporter's billing or statement, give Transporter written notification setting forth the disputed amount and the basis therefor. If any due date for payments does not occur on a business day, the due date shall become the next business day following the original due date. For purposes of this Agreement, business days shall be Monday through Friday, excluding bank holidays.
14.3 Payments hereunder shall be made by check or bank draft of Shipper payable at par to Transporter. Upon thirty (30) days prior written notice by Transporter, Shipper shall make payments hereunder by electronic transfer of funds to an account specified by Transporter from time to time.
14.4 If the total amount billed is not paid when due, then any unpaid amount shall be subject to late payment interest, which interest shall be computed on an annualized basis and shall accrue at a rate equivalent to the lesser of (i) "Prime Rate" plus 3% or (ii) the maximum rate permitted by applicable law. "Prime Rate" shall be the prime rate on corporate loans at large U.S. money center commercial banks set forth in the Wall Street Journal "Money Rates" table on the first date of publication for the calendar month in which payment is due. Transporter shall render a late payment interest invoice and Shipper shall pay within (10) days of late payment interest invoice postmark date. If an invoice or late payment interest invoice remains unpaid at the beginning of a subsequent month, the late payment interest for that month shall be assessed in the same manner as stated above but using the subsequent month's "Money Rates" table.
14.5 If at any time, any payment is past due for more than five (5) days, Transporter may give written notice by certified mail of intent to suspend gas receipts and deliveries under this Agreement. If payment is not received within five (5) days after the date of Transporter's notice of intent to suspend receipts and deliveries, Transporter shall have the right to suspend receipts and deliveries under this Agreement without prejudice to any other remedy or remedies afforded Transporter under this Agreement or by operation of law or equity. If such non-payment continues for another ten (10) days after suspension of receipts and deliveries, Transporter may terminate this Agreement upon written notice by certified mail to Shipper without prejudice to any other remedy or remedies afforded Transporter under this Agreement or by operation of law or equity.
14.6 Subsequent to any bill having been paid, if any overcharge or undercharge in any form whatsoever shall be found, appropriate compensating adjustments shall be made, and, if necessary, Transporter shall refund to Shipper or Shipper shall make an additional payment to Transporter, (whichever the case may be) within ten (10) days after final determination thereof; provided, however, no retroactive adjustments shall be made for any overcharge or undercharge beyond a period of twenty-four (24) months from the date of the original invoice(s).
ARTICLE XV. Financial Responsibility
15.1 Prior to commencement of service or at any time thereafter, Transporter may require Shipper to supply Transporter with credit information including, but not limited to, bank references, financial statements and names of persons with whom Shipper has recently transacted business in order that Transporter may make reasonable inquiry into Shipper's creditworthiness and obtain adequate assurance of Shipper's solvency and ability to perform. If at any time Transporter, in its sole opinion, is not satisfied with Shipper's credit or ability to perform or if Shipper has not paid invoices strictly in accordance with this Agreement for service provided hereunder, Transporter shall have the right to demand reasonable security for payment, require prepayment in cash, change to a more frequent billing basis than a monthly billing cycle, or demand such other satisfactory security as is, in Transporter's sole opinion, reasonable under the circumstances to protect Transporter's interests. Pending Shipper's compliance with Transporter's demand, Transporter shall have the right to suspend service hereunder. If Shipper does not comply with Transporter's demand within fifteen (15) days of Transporter's demand, Transporter shall have the right to terminate this Agreement.
ARTICLE XVI. Audit Rights
16.1 Each Party shall have the right at all reasonable times to audit the records of the other Party which are pertinent to this Agreement; provided, however, that each Party shall adequately protect the confidentiality of proprietary information. If any such examinations reveal any inaccuracy in any billing theretofore made, the necessary adjustments in such billing and payment shall be made within thirty (30) days after final determination thereof; provided that no adjustments for any billing or payment shall be made for any inaccuracy claimed after the lapse of twenty-four (24) months from the rendition of the invoice(s) relating thereto.
16.2 All of the accounting records and accounts referred to herein shall be maintained according to generally accepted accounting principles employed in the business of the purchase, transportation, and sales of gas or in accordance with any laws, rules, or regulations which are or may become applicable, and such records and accounts will be available for inspection at times mutually agreeable to the Parties hereto.
ARTICLE XVII. Responsibility
17.1 Shipper shall be deemed to be in exclusive control and possession of the gas until such gas shall have been received by Transporter at the Receipt Point and after such gas shall have been delivered at the Delivery Point. Transporter shall be deemed to be in exclusive control and possession of the gas after receipt of the gas at the Receipt Point and until such gas shall have been delivered to Shipper at the Delivery Point. As between the Parties hereto, the Party deemed to be in exclusive control and possession of the gas hereunder shall be responsible for anything which may be done, happen or arise with respect to such gas. Transporter's responsibility with respect to Shipper's gas shall be deemed to be met if Transporter exercised due diligence in protecting such gas.
17.2 It is understood and agreed that the gas delivered by Transporter for Shipper pursuant to this Agreement will not be odorized. Any odorization that is required by any applicable state or federal statute, order, rule, or regulation at the location beyond the Delivery Point shall be the sole responsibility of Shipper. Shipper agrees to indemnify and hold harmless Transporter from any and all losses or damages that may be incurred as the result of the operation and maintenance of odorization facilities or equipment at or near the Point of Delivery or that results from the failure of Shipper to properly odorize gas delivered by Transporter for the account of Shipper.
17.3 Each Party assumes full responsibility and liability arising from the installation, ownership, and operation of its pipelines and facilities and shall hold harmless the other Party from any claim, loss, expense or liability (except as otherwise specifically provided in this Agreement) that such Party incurs on account of such installation, ownership, and operation. However, a Party shall not be liable to the other Party for, or hold harmless the other Party from, any claims, loss, expense, or liability arising out of acts or omissions of third parties when such acts or omissions are not reasonably within the first Party's control.
ARTICLE XVIII. Warranty
18.1 Shipper warrants that upon delivery of gas to Transporter for transportation hereunder, Shipper, or the party(ies) for whom Shipper is having gas transported, will have good title or the good right to deliver such gas, and that such gas shall be free and clear of all liens, encumbrances and adverse claims. Shipper shall indemnify and hold harmless Transporter from and against all suits, actions, debts, accounts, damages, costs (including attorneys' fees), losses and expenses arising out of or in connection with any adverse claims of any and all persons regarding said gas.
18.2 Shipper represents and warrants that it (i) is an "interstate pipeline" within the meaning of Section 2(15) and Section 311 of the NGPA and Subpart C of Part 284 of the Commission's regulations, or (ii) is a "local distribution company served by any interstate pipeline" within the meaning of Section 2(17) and Section 311 of the NGPA and Subpart C of Part 284 of the Commission's regulations, or (iii) is authorized to arrange transportation pursuant to Section 311 of the NGPA on behalf of such interstate pipeline or local distribution company. Shipper also represents and warrants that it has arranged for the delivery and/or receipt by any necessary third-party transporter(s) of gas to be transported hereunder. Shipper shall indemnify and hold harmless Transporter from all suits, actions, damages, costs, losses, expenses (including attorneys' fees) and regulatory proceedings arising out of or in connection with breach of said warranty.
ARTICLE XIX. Force Majeure
19.1 In the event either Party is rendered unable, wholly or in part, by force majeure to carry out its obligations under this Agreement, other than the obligation to make payments of amounts due hereunder, it is agreed that, on such Party's giving notice and reasonably full particulars of such force majeure, in writing or by telegraph, to the other Party within a reasonable time after the occurrence of the cause relied on, the obligations of the Party giving such notice, so far as they are affected by such force majeure, shall be suspended during the continuance of any inability so caused, but for no longer period, and such cause shall, so far as possible, be remedied with all reasonable dispatch.
The term "force majeure," as employed herein, shall mean acts of God; strikes, lockouts or other industrial disturbances; acts of the public enemy, wars, blockades, insurrections, civil disturbances and riots, and epidemics; landslides, lightning, earthquakes, fires, storms, floods and washouts; arrests, orders, directives, restraints and requirements of the government and governmental agencies, either federal or state, civil and military; any application of governmental conservation rules and regulations; explosions, breakage or accident to machinery or lines of pipe; outages; (shutdowns) of power plant equipment or lines of pipe for inspection, maintenance or repair; freezing of wells or lines of pipe; and any other causes, whether of the kind enumerated or otherwise, not reasonably within the control of the Party claiming suspension. And the term "force majeure" shall also include (a) in those instances where either Party hereto is required to obtain servitudes, right-of-way grants, permits or licenses to enable such Party to fulfill its obligations hereunder, the inability of such Party in acquiring, at reasonable cost, and after the exercise of reasonable diligence, such servitudes, right-of-way grants, permits or licenses, and (b) in those instances where either Party hereto is required to furnish materials and supplies for the purpose of constructing or maintaining facilities or is required to secure permits or permission from any governmental agency to enable such Party to fulfill its obligations hereunder, the inability of such Party to acquire, or the delays on the part of such Party in acquiring, at reasonable cost and after the exercise of reasonable diligence, such materials and supplies, permits and permissions. It is understood and agreed that the settlement of strikes or lockouts shall be entirely within the discretion of the Party having the difficulty, and that the above reasonable dispatch shall not require the settlement of strikes or lockouts by acceding to the demand of the opposing party when such course is or is deemed to be inadvisable or inappropriate in the discretion of the Party having the difficulty.
ARTICLE XX. Remedy for Breach
20.1 Except as otherwise specifically provided herein, if either Party shall fail to perform any of the covenants or obligations imposed upon it in this Agreement (except where such failure shall be excused under the provisions of Article XIX. hereof), then, and in that event, the other Party may, at its option (without waiving any other remedy for breach hereof), by notice in writing specifying wherein the default has occurred, indicate such Party's election to terminate the Agreement by reason thereof. The Party in default shall have thirty (30) days from receipt of such notice to remedy such default and to pay or indemnify the other Party for all loss or damage incurred as a result thereof, and upon failure to do so, this Agreement shall terminate from and after the expiration of such thirty (30) day period. Any such termination shall be an additional remedy and shall not prejudice the right of the Party not in default to collect any amounts due it hereunder for any damage or loss suffered by it and shall not waive any other remedy to which the Party not in default may be entitled for breach of this Agreement.
20.2 The failure of either Party hereto at any time to require performance by the other Party of any provision of the Agreement shall in no way affect the right of such Party thereafter to enforce the same, nor shall the waiver by either Party of any breach of any provision hereof by the other Party be taken or held to be a waiver by such Party of any succeeding breach of such provision, or as a waiver of the provision itself.
ARTICLE XXI. Assignment
21.1 This Agreement shall be binding upon and inure to the benefit of the Parties hereto and their respective successors and assigns. However, this Agreement shall not be transferred or assigned by either Party without the prior written consent of the other Party; provided, however, that either Party shall have the right to assign this Agreement, in whole or in part, to an affiliated or subsidiary corporation or to any affiliated or subsidiary corporation of its parent or related corporation without the consent of the other Party. Shipper hereby agrees that in the event Shipper assigns or conveys all or any part of the leaseholds covered by this Agreement, Shipper shall provide in each instrument of such assignment or conveyance that such leases are assigned (or conveyed) subject to the terms and provisions of this Agreement. Shipper shall require that the party or parties to whom such assignment or conveyance is made agree to be bound by the terms and provisions of this Agreement by executing each such instrument of assignment or conveyance. The effective date upon which the successors or assigns receiving such assignment or conveyance shall be bound by the terms and provisions of this Agreement shall be the date that proper instruments of such assignment or conveyance have been received by Transporter.
ARTICLE XXII Conditions Precedent
22.1 In the event deliveries of gas for transportation hereunder have not commenced within sixty (60) days after the effective date of this Agreement, either Party shall have the right to cancel this Agreement prior to such time as deliveries are tendered and accepted hereunder by giving prior written notice of such cancellation to the other Party. However, in the event it is necessary to install, modify, or replace facilities required to permit the receipt or delivery of gas by Transporter hereunder, the right of either Party to cancel this Agreement pursuant to this Article XXII. shall accrue at the time such facilities are ready for service. Transporter shall be under no obligation to commence service under this Agreement unless and until (i) all facilities, of whatever nature, as are required to permit the receipt, measurement, transportation and delivery of gas hereunder have been installed and are in operating condition, and (ii) Shipper has arranged for the delivery and receipt by any necessary third-party transporter of gas to be transported hereunder by Transporter.
ARTICLE XXIII. Modification
23.1 Transporter reserves the right, at any time and from time to time, to modify or revise this Statement of General Terms and Standard Operating Conditions. Such modification or revisions shall be provided in writing to Shipper and shall be effective upon the first day of the month following transmittal to Shipper. Other modifications to this Agreement shall be or become effective only upon the due and mutual execution of appropriate supplemental agreements or amendments hereto by duly authorized representatives of the respective Parties.
ARTICLE XXIV. Rate Election
24.1 Transporter has elected to utilize the provisions of Section 284.123(b)(1)(i)(A) of the Commission’s Regulations to establish the maximum rates which Transporter may charge for interruptible transportation service rendered pursuant to NGPA Section 311(a)(2).
